I fell into the whole trap of being the "cool girl" and the whole social positioning of being friends with guys when I was in high school. I love my guy friends to death, they're like my brothers. But I find it harder to make friends with fellow females. Like I haven't successfully been able to socialize myself well enough around women. So now, as a mid-20 something, I'm struggling to create the proper script around women. It's so difficult because I have so many women around me that I admire and I want to tell them that. But at a young age I never had the chance to learn to interact well with women.

I am happy that a person like you exists on the internet because now whenever I want to express my thoughts to my niece and younger female cousin, I can just link your videos, and then supplement them with my own thoughts.

snippet.textDisplay: I've struggled with my sexual identity my whole life, and in middle and elementary school all I based my 'popularity' off of was a man. I really wanted male attention. Of course, that's the social Norm, especially in my school, a girl had a 'popular' boyfriend, boom, you were in turn, popular. I dated alot of 'unpopular' boys, but I ALWAYS felt cool when I could say I was 'owned' by someday. It was always one relationship to the other. Then I fell in love with a girl at my private school, and i jumped straight into that one. Than, now that I was dubbed 'the male' of the relationship, I felt really free to think(its sad). I looked towards my future as an artist in highschool, and this narrative lead to a gross breakup with my girlfriend for other two years, and in that two month period, We both found what it is to be independent, as ourselves. I had found myself, changed style and everything, and loved it. Now, Three years and continuing, with the girl of my dreams, we both understand our worth, and I couldn't be happier to say I'm a lesbian. Point is, even if you never think you're never going to get out of the same mindset, you are. It takes time. And being in a relationship doesn't mean you aren't strong. It means you are strong enough to separate yourself from someone else's personality in order to make something beautiful flourish. Plus, being single means more ME TIME! I take me time all the time, it isn't bad to be alone, even if you're in a relationship.

snippet.textDisplay: Your twenties are for experimenting and creating amazing memories. You have the energy and the drive and the audacity to jump in and try new things, so do so, repeatedly.  Yes sometimes you do need to fight against that evolutionary drive to nab someone quickly, but it is just that, a genetic imperative from the past, to feel we as women need to be perfect, to quickly find a mate and create offspring.  Feeling like that is not you being a subpar woman, who is failing at feminism, its just that your brain has been partially hijacked by a biological drive. Self confidence and learning not to apologize for yourself does become easier as you get older, and fears do fade.  But energy can dwindle, so make tons of mistakes and learn and fail and grow now, without regret.  And always, always, practice creating the habit of being kind to yourself.  Gently call yourself out on your internal (and external) dialogue, and treat yourself with the compassion you would give to your own best friend.  From someone who is approaching fifty,  the reality is your  life isnt being judged by anyone but yourself.  There are no 'congratulations you passed' final exams when you get older.  We will always be reaching for something more while simultaneously reminiscing about what we once had, that never changes.  Worry less about what you believe others think of you, because the truth is they very rarely do, and just do the best to live the most amazing and rewarding life that you can, whatever that looks like.
